{"/service/ndnp/tu/batch_tu_dinah_ver01/data/sn98069867/00415621723/1920121001/1091.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE NINE.\nFRIDAY, DECEMBER 10j 1920.\nEx-Private Elected\nNeW Legion Leader\nF\nTHE NEWS SCIMITAK.\nRETAIL GROCERS\nEAST AND TALK\nNominations for Officers Are\nMade at Chamber of Com\nmerce Banquet.\nThomas O. Mallon, secretary of\nthe Tennessee State Retail Grocers'\nassociation, was the principal speak\ner at a mooting held by the local\n9\nbranch of the organization in the\ndining hall of the Chamber, of Com\nmerce Thursday night. He spoke\nof the work of the state organization,\nshowing that several bill detrimental\nto the retail grocery trade were de\nfeated by its efforts.\nMr. Mallon also spoke of the five\nbills to be submitted to the next\nsession of legislature.\nFollowing Mallon, Sam. McDonald\nspoke on. the advantages of organi\nzation. The last speaker was Mayor Row\nlett Paine. He told the assemblage\nthat he was more at home in that\natmosphere than he had been for\nmany a day, saying that before be\ncoming engaged in public affairs he\nWas a wholesale grocer, and knew\na number of the retail grocers in\ntimately. He gave a brief history of\nthe city of Memphis, its politics and\nfinances. He said that to him the\nbusiness outlook is good.\nDuring the speaking a banquet was\nserved, and selections by the male\nquartet were rendered. J. W. Shep\nherd acted as toastmaster.\nNominations for the coming elec\ntion were: F. L. Swantz for presi\ndent: first vice-president, O. W.\nWoodberry and Ed Fells; second\nvice-president, J. M. Garrett; for\nmembers of the committee, which is\nlimited to five, B. N. Sawtelle, A. T.\nF. Viani, P. E. Mergle, E. Phillips,\nSam Abraham, J. T. Phipps, Wm.\nKrayer, Geo. Schmidt, A. Martini,\nGeo. Burkle and J. J. Herrlck were\nnominated. The time of election will\nbe decided later.\nWill Seek Flexible\nSalary Arrangement\nJohn B. Edgar, commissioner of\nfire and police, will ask the Shelby\ndelegation to the legislature to cham\npion a bill providing for- a flexible\nsalary for firemen and policemen by\nfixing a maximum and minimum sal\nary which may be paid by the city\ncommission.\nMr. Edgar wants this arrangement\nmade, so that the city commission\nmay raise or lower the 'salaries of\nthe men In the departments in ac\nocrdance with the rise and fall of\nsalaries in commercial lines. He\npoints out that if this is done ati\nappeal to the legislature for legisla\ntion will not. be necessary every time\nthe salaries in the departments are\nfound to be out of line with those\npaid in. other callings.\nThe legal department of the ctty\nwill be asked to draw up the pro\nposed measure.\nANDREW 8. LAWO.\nAnflrAW S TjLWO. who is COH\nnected with the City Coal company,\nBuw u. o r\nprivate to be elected commander or\nt.. nat 'n 1. American\n.u tiijiinn\nLegion, the two former commanders\nboth having been orncers. wiro\n.n i.tui n thnt nonition unani-\nnaa i\nmmmiv it a meetiner at the Chamber\nof Commerce Thursday night.\nOther officers elected were: w. u.\nTerry, vice-commander; Rembert\n.ini.nt' Wrwln Harris, treas-\nillUlll, nujubu..\nurer; W. I Kuss, sergeant-at-arms,\nand K. J. Foster, joe iiurvmo m\nR. C. Reeves, members of the execu\ntive committee.\nCOTTON MILLS REOPEN.\ntit i tt rHmT XT r TYf 1 fl Villi\ntime operations of the Highland Park\nCotton nuns ai timnuiw- i\ni i- nnur lint Clhristmafl.\nmuunutiiii ,uii\neivlne employment to approximately\n6,000 workers, was officially an\nnounced. The mills nave neen mie sev\neral weeks. Officials of the company\ndeclined to say whether tne mms wouia\nbe operated after unrwmu.\n(When You Think\n(that you cannot take\ncod-liver oil, the\ni evidence is clear mat\nI you have not taken\nScott's Emulsion\nI recently. Ifs as rich I\nI a fis us cream, onlv\nmore easily as- 5\nsimilated and is I\npleasant to take,\nS?o?t Hownf? Bloornflftd.N J 20-SS\nThese are the best\nbicycles made and\nare sold under a guar\nantee. Come in and get\ninformati